# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: kmp-string-matching
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] In computer science, the **Boyer–Moore string-search algorithm** is an efficient string-searching algorithm that is the standard benchmark for practical string-search literature.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The original paper contained static tables for computing the pattern shifts without an explanation of how to produce them.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The algorithm for producing the tables was published in a follow-on paper; this paper contained errors which were later corrected by Wojciech Rytter in 1980.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The algorithm preprocesses the string being searched for (the pattern), but not the string being searched in (the text).
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] It is thus well-suited for applications in which the pattern is much shorter than the text or where it persists across multiple searches.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The Boyer–Moore algorithm uses information gathered during the preprocess step to skip sections of the text, resulting in a lower constant factor than many other string search algorithms.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] In general, the algorithm runs faster as the pattern length increases.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The key features of the algorithm are to match on the tail of the pattern rather than the head, and to skip along the text in jumps of multiple characters rather than searching every single character in the text.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The Boyer–Moore algorithm searches for occurrences of P in T by performing explicit character comparisons at different alignments.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Instead of a brute-force search of all alignments (of which there are ⁠ $n-m+1$ ⁠), Boyer–Moore uses information gained by preprocessing P to skip as many alignments as possible.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Previous to the introduction of this algorithm, the usual way to search within text was to examine each character of the text for the first character of the pattern.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Once that was found the subsequent characters of the text would be compared to the characters of the pattern.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] If no match occurred then the text would again be checked character by character in an effort to find a match.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Thus almost every character in the text needs to be examined.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The key insight in this algorithm is that if the end of the pattern is compared to the text, then jumps along the text can be made rather than checking every character of the text.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The reason that this works is that in lining up the pattern against the text, the last character of the pattern is compared to the character in the text.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] If the characters do not match, there is no need to continue searching backwards along the text.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] If the character in the text does not match any of the characters in the pattern, then the next character in the text to check is located m characters farther along the text, where m is the length of the pattern.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] If the character in the text *is* in the pattern, then a partial shift of the pattern along the text is done to line up along the matching character and the process is repeated.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Jumping along the text to make comparisons rather than checking every character in the text decreases the number of comparisons that have to be made, which is the key to the efficiency of the algorithm.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] More formally, the algorithm begins at alignment ⁠ $k=m$ ⁠, so the start of P is aligned with the start of T.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Characters in P and T are then compared starting at index m in P and k in T, moving backward.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The strings are matched from the end of P to the start of P.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The comparisons continue until either the beginning of P is reached (which means there is a match) or a mismatch occurs upon which the alignment is shifted forward (to the right) according to the maximum value permitted by a number of rules.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The comparisons are performed again at the new alignment, and the process repeats until the alignment is shifted past the end of T, which means no further matches will be found.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The shift rules are implemented as constant-time table lookups, using tables generated during the preprocessing of P.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] A shift is calculated by applying two rules: the bad-character rule and the good-suffix rule.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The actual shifting offset is the maximum of the shifts calculated by these rules.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The bad-character rule considers the character in T at which the comparison process failed (assuming such a failure occurred).
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The next occurrence of that character to the left in P is found, and a shift which brings that occurrence in line with the mismatched occurrence in T is proposed.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] If the mismatched character does not occur to the left in P, a shift is proposed that moves the entirety of P past the point of mismatch.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Methods vary on the exact form the table for the bad-character rule should take, but a simple constant-time lookup solution is as follows: create a 2D table which is indexed first by the index of the character c in the alphabet and second by the index i in the pattern.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] This lookup will return the occurrence of c in P with the next-highest index ⁠ $j<i$ ⁠ or -1 if there is no such occurrence.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The proposed shift will then be ⁠ $i-j$ ⁠, with ⁠ $O(1)$ ⁠ lookup time and ⁠ $O(km)$ ⁠ space, assuming a finite alphabet of length k.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The C and Java implementations below have a ⁠ $O(k)$ ⁠ space complexity (make_delta1, makeCharTable).
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] This is the same as the original delta1 and the BMH bad-character table.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] This table maps a character at position ⁠ i ⁠ to shift by ⁠ $\operatorname {len} (p)-1-i$ ⁠, with the last instance—the least shift amount—taking precedence.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] All unused characters are set as ⁠ $\operatorname {len} (p)$ ⁠ as a sentinel value.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The good-suffix rule is markedly more complex in both concept and implementation than the bad-character rule.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Like the bad-character rule, it also exploits the algorithm's feature of comparisons beginning at the end of the pattern and proceeding towards the pattern's start.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The good-suffix rule requires two tables: one for use in the general case (where a copy ***t′*** is found), and another for use when the general case returns no meaningful result.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] These tables will be designated L and H respectively.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Both of these tables are constructible in ⁠ $O(m)$ ⁠ time and use ⁠ $O(m)$ ⁠ space.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The alignment shift for index i in P is given by ⁠ $m-L[i]$ ⁠ or ⁠ $m-H[i]$ ⁠.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] H should only be used if ⁠ $L[i]$ ⁠ is zero or a match has been found.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Index 0, no characters matched, the character read was not an N.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Since there are plenty of letters in the pattern that are also not N, we have minimal information here - shifting by 1 is the least interesting result.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Index 1, we matched the N, and it was preceded by something other than A.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Now look at the pattern starting from the end, where do we have N preceded by something other than A?
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] There are two other N's, but both are preceded by A.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] That means no part of the good suffix can be useful to us—shift by the full pattern length 8.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Index 2: We matched the AN, and it was preceded by not M.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] In the middle of the pattern there is a AN preceded by P, so it becomes the shift candidate.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Shifting that AN to the right to line up with our match is a shift of 3.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Index 3 & up: the matched suffixes do not match anything else in the pattern, but the trailing suffix AN matches the start of the pattern, so the shifts here are all 6.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] A simple but important optimization of Boyer–Moore was put forth by Zvi Galil in 1979.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] As opposed to shifting, the Galil rule deals with speeding up the actual comparisons done at each alignment by skipping sections that are known to match.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Suppose that at an alignment *k*1, ***P*** is compared with ***T*** down to character ***c*** of ***T***.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Then if ***P*** is shifted to *k*2 such that its left end is between ***c*** and *k*1, in the next comparison phase a prefix of ***P*** must match the substring ***T***[(*k*2 - *n*)..*k*1].
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Thus if the comparisons get down to position *k*1 of ***T***, an occurrence of ***P*** can be recorded without explicitly comparing past *k*1.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] In addition to increasing the efficiency of Boyer–Moore, the Galil rule is required for proving linear-time execution in the worst case.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The Galil rule, in its original version, is only effective for versions that output multiple matches.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] It updates the substring range only on ***c*** = 0, i.e. a full match.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] A generalized version for dealing with submatches was reported in 1985 as the Apostolico–Giancarlo algorithm.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The Boyer–Moore algorithm as presented in the original paper has worst-case running time of ⁠ $O(n+m)$ ⁠ only if the pattern does *not* appear in the text.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] This was first proved by Knuth, Morris, and Pratt in 1977, followed by Guibas and Odlyzko in 1980 with an upper bound of 5*n* comparisons in the worst case.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Richard Cole gave a proof with an upper bound of 3*n* comparisons in the worst case in 1991.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] There is a simple modification of the BM algorithm which improves the bound to 2*n*.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] When the pattern *does* occur in the text, running time of the original algorithm is ⁠ $O(nm)$ ⁠ in the worst case.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] This is easy to see when both pattern and text consist solely of the same repeated character.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] However, inclusion of the Galil rule results in linear runtime across all cases.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Knuth, Morris and Pratt also showed that for a *random* text, the average number of character comparisons is bounded by $O\left({\frac {n\log _{k}m}{m}}\right)$ , where k is the alphabet size.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Various implementations exist in different programming languages.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] In C++ it is part of the Standard Library since C++17 and Boost provides the generic Boyer–Moore search implementation under the *Algorithm* library.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] In Go (programming language) there is an implementation in search.go.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] D (programming language) uses a BoyerMooreFinder for predicate based matching within ranges as a part of the Phobos Runtime Library.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The Boyer–Moore algorithm is also used in GNU's grep.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The Boyer–Moore–Horspool algorithm is a simplification of the Boyer–Moore algorithm using only the bad-character rule.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The Apostolico–Giancarlo algorithm speeds up the process of checking whether a match has occurred at the given alignment by skipping explicit character comparisons.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] This uses information gleaned during the pre-processing of the pattern in conjunction with suffix match lengths recorded at each match attempt.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] Storing suffix match lengths requires an additional table equal in size to the text being searched.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The Raita algorithm improves the performance of Boyer–Moore–Horspool algorithm.
[src:kmp-string-matching/boyer-moore-string-search-algorithm] The searching pattern of particular sub-string in a given string is different from Boyer–Moore–Horspool algorithm.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] In theoretical computer science, a **finite-state machine** (**FSM**) or **finite-state automaton** (**FSA**, plural: *automata*), **finite automaton**, or simply a **state machine**, is a mathematical model of computation.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] It is an abstract machine that can be in exactly one of a finite number of *states* at any given time.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] The FSM can change from one state to another in response to some inputs; the change from one state to another is called a *transition*.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] An FSM is defined by a list of its states, its initial state, and the inputs that trigger each transition.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] Finite-state machines are of two types—deterministic finite-state machines and non-deterministic finite-state machines.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] For any non-deterministic finite-state machine, an equivalent deterministic one can be constructed.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] The behavior of state machines can be observed in many devices in modern society that perform a predetermined sequence of actions depending on a sequence of events with which they are presented.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] The finite-state machine has less computational power than some other models of computation such as the Turing machine.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] The computational power distinction means there are computational tasks that a Turing machine can do but an FSM cannot.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] This is because an FSM's memory is limited by the number of states it has.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] A finite-state machine has the same computational power as a Turing machine that is restricted such that its head may only perform "read" operations, and always has to move from left to right.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] FSMs are studied in the more general field of automata theory.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] An example of a simple mechanism that can be modeled by a state machine is a turnstile.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] A turnstile, used to control access to subways and amusement park rides, is a gate with three rotating arms at waist height, one across the entryway.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] Initially the arms are locked, blocking the entry, preventing patrons from passing through.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] Depositing a coin or token in a slot on the turnstile unlocks the arms, allowing a single customer to push through.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] After the customer passes through, the arms are locked again until another coin is inserted.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] Considered as a state machine, the turnstile has two possible states: *Locked* and *Unlocked*.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] There are two possible inputs that affect its state: putting a coin in the slot (*coin*) and pushing the arm (*push*).
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] In the locked state, pushing on the arm has no effect; no matter how many times the input *push* is given, it stays in the locked state.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] Putting a coin in – that is, giving the machine a *coin* input – shifts the state from *Locked* to *Unlocked*.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] In the unlocked state, putting additional coins in has no effect; that is, giving additional *coin* inputs does not change the state.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] A customer pushing through the arms gives a *push* input and resets the state to *Locked*.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] The turnstile state machine can also be represented by a directed graph called a state diagram *(above)*.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] Each state is represented by a node (*circle*).
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] Edges (*arrows*) show the transitions from one state to another.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] Each arrow is labeled with the input that triggers that transition.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] An input that doesn't cause a change of state (such as a *coin* input in the *Unlocked* state) is represented by a circular arrow returning to the original state.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] The arrow into the *Locked* node from the black dot indicates it is the initial state.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] A *state* is a description of the status of a system that is waiting to execute a *transition*.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] A transition is a set of actions to be executed when a condition is fulfilled or when an event is received.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] For example, when using an audio system to listen to the radio (the system is in the "radio" state), receiving a "next" stimulus results in moving to the next station.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] When the system is in the "CD" state, the "next" stimulus results in moving to the next track.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] Identical stimuli trigger different actions depending on the current state.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] Several state-transition table types are used.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] The most common representation is shown below: the combination of current state (e.g.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] By itself, the table cannot completely describe the action, so it is common to use footnotes.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] Other related representations may not have this limitation.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] For example, an FSM definition including the full action's information is possible using state tables (see also virtual finite-state machine).
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] The Unified Modeling Language has a notation for describing state machines.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] UML state machines overcome the limitations of traditional finite-state machines while retaining their main benefits.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] UML state machines introduce the new concepts of hierarchically nested states and orthogonal regions, while extending the notion of actions.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] UML state machines have the characteristics of both Mealy machines and Moore machines.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] They support actions that depend on both the state of the system and the triggering event, as in Mealy machines, as well as entry and exit actions, which are associated with states rather than transitions, as in Moore machines.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] SDL embeds basic data types called "Abstract Data Types", an action language, and an execution semantic in order to make the finite-state machine executable.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] There are a large number of variants to represent an FSM such as the one in figure 3.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] In addition to their use in modeling reactive systems presented here, finite-state machines are significant in many different areas, including electrical engineering, linguistics, computer science, philosophy, biology, mathematics, video game programming, and logic.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] Finite-state machines are a class of automata studied in automata theory and the theory of computation.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] In computer science, finite-state machines are widely used in modeling of application behavior (control theory), design of hardware digital systems, software engineering, compilers, network protocols, and computational linguistics.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] Finite-state machines can be subdivided into acceptors, classifiers, transducers and sequencers.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] A (possibly infinite) set of symbol sequences, called a formal language, is a regular language if there is some acceptor that accepts *exactly* that set.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] For example, the set of binary strings with an even number of zeroes is a regular language (cf.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] 5), while the set of all strings whose length is a prime number is not.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] An acceptor could also be described as defining a language that would contain every string accepted by the acceptor but none of the rejected ones; that language is *accepted* by the acceptor.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] By definition, the languages accepted by acceptors are the regular languages.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] The problem of determining the language accepted by a given acceptor is an instance of the algebraic path problem—itself a generalization of the shortest path problem to graphs with edges weighted by the elements of an (arbitrary) semiring.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] An example of an accepting state appears in Fig.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] 5: a deterministic finite automaton (DFA) that detects whether the binary input string contains an even number of 0s.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] The FSM uses only entry actions, i.e., output depends only on state.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] The advantage of the Moore model is a simplification of the behaviour.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] The state machine recognizes two commands: "command_open" and "command_close", which trigger state changes.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] The entry action (E:) in state "Opening" starts a motor opening the door, the entry action in state "Closing" starts a motor in the other direction closing the door.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] States "Opened" and "Closed" stop the motor when fully opened or closed.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] They signal to the outside world (e.g., to other state machines) the situation: "door is open" or "door is closed".
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] The FSM also uses input actions, i.e., output depends on input and state.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] The use of a Mealy FSM leads often to a reduction of the number of states.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] There are two input actions (I:): "start motor to close the door if command_close arrives" and "start motor in the other direction to open the door if command_open arrives".
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] The "opening" and "closing" intermediate states are not shown.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] A further distinction is between *deterministic* (DFA) and *non-deterministic* (NFA, GNFA) automata.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] In a deterministic automaton, every state has exactly one transition for each possible input.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] In a non-deterministic automaton, an input can lead to one, more than one, or no transition for a given state.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] The powerset construction algorithm can transform any nondeterministic automaton into a (usually more complex) deterministic automaton with identical functionality.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] A finite-state machine with only one state is called a "combinatorial FSM".
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] It only allows actions upon transition *into* a state.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] This concept is useful in cases where a number of finite-state machines are required to work together, and when it is convenient to consider a purely combinatorial part as a form of FSM to suit the design tools.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] There are other sets of semantics available to represent state machines.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] For example, there are tools for modeling and designing logic for embedded controllers.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] They combine hierarchical state machines (which usually have more than one current state), flow graphs, and truth tables into one language, resulting in a different formalism and set of semantics.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] These charts, like Harel's original state machines, support hierarchically nested states, orthogonal regions, state actions, and transition actions.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] In accordance with the general classification, the following formal definitions are found.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] For both deterministic and non-deterministic FSMs, it is conventional to allow $\delta$ to be a partial function, i.e. $\delta (s,x)$ does not have to be defined for every combination of $s\in S$ and $x\in \Sigma$ .
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] If an FSM M is in a state s , the next symbol is x and $\delta (s,x)$ is not defined, then M can announce an error (i.e. reject the input).
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] This is useful in definitions of general state machines, but less useful when transforming the machine.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] Some algorithms in their default form may require total functions.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] That is, each formal language accepted by a finite-state machine is accepted by such a kind of restricted Turing machine, and vice versa.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] If the output function depends on the state and input symbol ( $\omega :S\times \Sigma \rightarrow \Gamma$ ) that definition corresponds to the *Mealy model*, and can be modelled as a Mealy machine.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] If the output function depends only on the state ( $\omega :S\rightarrow \Gamma$ ) that definition corresponds to the *Moore model*, and can be modelled as a Moore machine.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] A finite-state machine with no output function at all is known as a semiautomaton or transition system.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] If we disregard the first output symbol of a Moore machine, $\omega (s_{0})$ , then it can be readily converted to an output-equivalent Mealy machine by setting the output function of every Mealy transition (i.e. labeling every edge) with the output symbol given of the destination Moore state.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] The converse transformation is less straightforward because a Mealy machine state may have different output labels on its incoming transitions (edges).
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] Every such state needs to be split in multiple Moore machine states, one for every incident output symbol.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] Optimizing an FSM means finding a machine with the minimum number of states that performs the same function.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] The fastest known algorithm doing this is the Hopcroft minimization algorithm.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] Other techniques include using an implication table, or the Moore reduction procedure.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] Additionally, acyclic FSAs can be minimized in linear time.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] In a digital circuit, an FSM may be built using a programmable logic device, a programmable logic controller, logic gates and flip flops or relays.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] More specifically, a hardware implementation requires a register to store state variables, a block of combinational logic that determines the state transition, and a second block of combinational logic that determines the output of an FSM.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] In a *Medvedev machine*, the output is directly connected to the state flip-flops minimizing the time delay between flip-flops and output.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] Through state encoding for low power state machines may be optimized to minimize power consumption.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] Finite automata are often used in the frontend of programming language compilers.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] Such a frontend may comprise several finite-state machines that implement a lexical analyzer and a parser.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] Starting from a sequence of characters, the lexical analyzer builds a sequence of language tokens (such as reserved words, literals, and identifiers) from which the parser builds a syntax tree.
[src:kmp-string-matching/finite-state-machine] The lexical analyzer and the parser handle the regular and context-free parts of the programming language's grammar.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Morris and independently discovered by Donald Knuth "a few weeks later" from automata theory.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Morris and Vaughan Pratt published a technical report in 1970.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The three also published the algorithm jointly in 1977.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Independently, in 1969, Matiyasevich discovered a similar algorithm, coded by a two-dimensional Turing machine, while studying a string-pattern-matching recognition problem over a binary alphabet.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] This was the first linear-time algorithm for string matching.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] A string-matching algorithm wants to find the starting index `m` in string `s` that matches the search word `w`.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The most straightforward algorithm, known as the "brute-force" or "naive" algorithm, is to look for a word match at each index `m`, i.e. the position in the string being searched that corresponds to the character `s[m]`.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] At each position `m` the algorithm first checks for equality of the first character in the word being searched, i.e.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] If a match is found, the algorithm tests the other characters in the word being searched by checking successive values of the word position index, `i`.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The algorithm retrieves the character `w[i]` in the word being searched and checks for equality of the expression `S[m+i] =?
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] If all successive characters match in `W` at position `m`, then a match is found at that position in the search string.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] If the index `m` reaches the end of the string then there is no match, in which case the search is said to "fail".
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Usually, the trial check will quickly reject the trial match.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] If the strings are uniformly distributed random letters, then the chance that characters match is 1 in 26.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] In most cases, the trial check will reject the match at the initial letter.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The chance that the first two letters will match is 1 in 676 (1 in 26^2 chances of a match over 26 possible letters).
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] So if the characters are random, then the expected complexity of searching string `s` of length *n* is on the order of *n* comparisons or *Θ*(*n*).
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] If `s` is 1 million characters and `w` is 1000 characters, then the string search should complete after about 1.04 million character comparisons.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] That expected performance is not guaranteed.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] If the strings are not random, then checking a trial `m` may take many character comparisons.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The worst case is if the two strings match in all but the last letter.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Imagine that the string `s` consists of 1 million characters that are all *A*, and that the word `w` is 999 *A* characters terminating in a final *B* character.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The simple string-matching algorithm will now examine 1000 characters at each trial position before rejecting the match and advancing the trial position.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The simple string search example would now take about 1000 character comparisons times 1 million positions for 1 billion character comparisons.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] If the length of `w` is *k*, then the worst-case performance is *O*(*k*⋅*n*).
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The KMP algorithm has a better worst-case performance than the straightforward algorithm.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] KMP spends a little time precomputing a table (on the order of the size of `w`, *O*(*k*)), and then it uses that table to do an efficient search of the string in *O*(*n*).
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The difference is that KMP makes use of previous match information that the straightforward algorithm does not.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] In the example above, when KMP sees a trial match fail on the 1000th character (`i` = 999) because `s[m + 999] ≠ w[999]`, it will increment `m` by 1, but it will know that the first 998 characters at the new position already match.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] KMP matched 999 *A* characters before discovering a mismatch at the 1000th character (position 999).
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Advancing the trial match position `m` by one throws away the first *A*, so KMP knows there are 998 *A* characters that match `w` and does not retest them; that is, KMP sets `i` to 998.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] KMP maintains its knowledge in the precomputed table and two state variables.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] When KMP discovers a mismatch, the table determines how much KMP will increase (variable `m`) and where it will resume testing (variable `i`).
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] To illustrate the algorithm's details, consider a (relatively artificial) run of the algorithm, where `W` = "ABCDABD" and `S` = "ABC ABCDAB ABCDABCDABDE".
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] In each step the algorithm compares `S[m+i]` with `W[i]` and increments `i` if they are equal.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The algorithm compares successive characters of `W` to "parallel" characters of `S`, moving from one to the next by incrementing `i` if they match.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] However, in the fourth step `S[3] = ' '` does not match `W[3] = 'D'`.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Rather than beginning to search again at `S[1]`, we note that no `'A'` occurs between positions 1 and 2 in `S`; hence, having checked all those characters previously (and knowing they matched the corresponding characters in `W`), there is no chance of finding the beginning of a match.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Therefore, the algorithm sets `m = 3` and `i = 0`.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Here, `i` increments through a nearly complete match `"ABCDAB"` until `i = 6` giving a mismatch at `W[6]` and `S[10]`.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] However, just prior to the end of the current partial match, there was that substring `"AB"` that could be the beginning of a new match, so the algorithm must take this into consideration.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] As these characters match the two characters prior to the current position, those characters need not be checked again; the algorithm sets `m = 8` (the start of the initial prefix) and `i = 2` (signaling the first two characters match) and continues matching.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Thus the algorithm not only omits previously matched characters of `S` (the `"AB"`), but also previously matched characters of `W` (the prefix `"AB"`).
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] This search at the new position fails immediately because `W[2]` (a `'C'`) does not match `S[10]` (a `' '`).
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] As in the first trial, the mismatch causes the algorithm to return to the beginning of `W` and begins searching at the mismatched character position of `S`: `m = 10`, reset `i = 0`.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The match at `m=10` fails immediately, so the algorithm next tries `m = 11` and `i = 0`.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Once again, the algorithm matches `"ABCDAB"`, but the next character, `'C'`, does not match the final character `'D'` of the word `W`.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Reasoning as before, the algorithm sets `m = 15`, to start at the two-character string `"AB"` leading up to the current position, set `i = 2`, and continue matching from the current position.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] This time the match is complete, and the first character of the match is `S[15]`.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The above example contains all the elements of the algorithm.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] For the moment, we assume the existence of a "partial match" table `T`, described below, which indicates where we need to look for the start of a new match when a mismatch is found.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The entries of `T` are constructed so that if we have a match starting at `S[m]` that fails when comparing `S[m + i]` to `W[i]`, then the next possible match will start at index `m + i - T[i]` in `S` (that is, `T[i]` is the amount of "backtracking" we need to do after a mismatch).
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The following is a sample pseudocode implementation of the KMP search algorithm.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Assuming the prior existence of the table `T`, the search portion of the Knuth–Morris–Pratt algorithm has complexity *O*(*n*), where *n* is the length of `S` and the *O* is big-O notation.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Except for the fixed overhead incurred in entering and exiting the function, all the computations are performed in the `**while**` loop.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] To bound the number of iterations of this loop; observe that `T` is constructed so that if a match which had begun at `S[m]` fails while comparing `S[m + i]` to `W[i]`, then the next possible match must begin at `S[m + (i - T[i])]`.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] In particular, the next possible match must occur at a higher index than `m`, so that `T[i] < i`.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] This fact implies that the loop can execute at most 2*n* times, since at each iteration it executes one of the two branches in the loop.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The first branch invariably increases `i` and does not change `m`, so that the index `m + i` of the currently scrutinized character of `S` is increased.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The second branch adds `i - T[i]` to `m`, and as we have seen, this is always a positive number.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Thus the location `m` of the beginning of the current potential match is increased.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] At the same time, the second branch leaves `m + i` unchanged, for `m` gets `i - T[i]` added to it, and immediately after `T[i]` gets assigned as the new value of `i`, hence `new_m + new_i = old_m + old_i - T[old_i] + T[old_i] = old_m + old_i`.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Thus the loop executes at most 2*n* times, showing that the time complexity of the search algorithm is *O*(*n*).
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Here is another way to think about the runtime: Let us say we begin to match `W` and `S` at position `i` and `p`.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] If `W` exists as a substring of `S` at p, then `W[0..m] = S[p..p+m]`.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Upon success, that is, the word and the text matched at the positions (`W[i] = S[p+i]`), we increase `i` by 1.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Upon failure, that is, the word and the text do not match at the positions (`W[i] ≠ S[p+i]`), the text pointer is kept still, while the word pointer is rolled back a certain amount (`i = T[i]`, where `T` is the jump table), and we attempt to match `W[T[i]]` with `S[p+i]`.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The maximum number of roll-back of `i` is bounded by `i`, that is to say, for any failure, we can only roll back as much as we have progressed up to the failure.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The goal of the table is to allow the algorithm not to match any character of `S` more than once.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] In other words, we "pre-search" the pattern itself and compile a list of all possible fallback positions that bypass a maximum of hopeless characters while not sacrificing any potential matches in doing so.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Hence `T[i]` is exactly the length of the longest possible *proper* initial segment of `W` which is also a segment of the substring ending at `W[i - 1]`.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] We use the convention that the empty string has length 0.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Since a mismatch at the very start of the pattern is a special case (there is no possibility of backtracking), we set `T[0] = -1`, as discussed below.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] We consider the example of `W = "ABCDABD"` first.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] We will see that it follows much the same pattern as the main search, and is efficient for similar reasons.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] To find `T[1]`, we must discover a proper suffix of `"A"` which is also a prefix of pattern `W`.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] But there are no proper suffixes of `"A"`, so we set `T[1] = 0`.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] However "B" is not a prefix of the pattern `W`.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Continuing to `T[3]`, we first check the proper suffix of length 1, and as in the previous case it fails.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Hence at each stage, the shortcut rule is that one needs to consider checking suffixes of a given size m+1 only if a valid suffix of size m was found at the previous stage (i.e.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] `T[x] = m`) and should not bother to check m+2, m+3, etc.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Therefore, we need not even concern ourselves with substrings having length 2, and as in the previous case the sole one with length 1 fails, so `T[3] = 0`.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] We pass to the subsequent `W[4]`, `'A'`.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The same logic shows that the longest substring we need to consider has length 1, and as in the previous case it fails since "D" is not a prefix of `W`.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] But instead of setting `T[4] = 0`, we can do better by noting that `W[4] = W[0]`, and also that a look-up of `T[4]` implies the corresponding `S` character, `S[m+4]`, was a mismatch and therefore `S[m+4] ≠ 'A'`.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Thus there is no point in restarting the search at `S[m+4]`; we should begin at 1 position ahead.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] This means that we may shift pattern `W` by match length plus one character, so `T[4] = -1`.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Considering now the next character, `W[5]`, which is `'B'`: though by inspection the longest substring would appear to be `'A'`, we still set `T[5] = 0`.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The reasoning is similar to why `T[4] = -1`.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] `W[5]` itself extends the prefix match begun with `W[4]`, and we can assume that the corresponding character in `S`, `S[m+5] ≠ 'B'`.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Finally, we see that the next character in the ongoing segment starting at `W[4] = 'A'` would be `'B'`, and indeed this is also `W[5]`.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Furthermore, the same argument as above shows that we need not look before `W[4]` to find a segment for `W[6]`, so that this is it, and we take `T[6] = 2`.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The example above illustrates the general technique for assembling the table with a minimum of fuss.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The principle is that of the overall search: most of the work was already done in getting to the current position, so very little needs to be done in leaving it.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The only minor complication is that the logic which is correct late in the string erroneously gives non-proper substrings at the beginning.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] This necessitates some initialization code.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The time (and space) complexity of the table algorithm is $O(k)$ , where k is the length of `W`.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Combined, the outer and inner loops take at most $2k-2$ iterations.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] This corresponds to $O(k)$ time complexity using the Big O notation.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Since the two portions of the algorithm have, respectively, complexities of `O(k)` and `O(n)`, the complexity of the overall algorithm is `O(n + k)`.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] These complexities are independent of how many repetitive patterns are in `W` or `S`.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] It is known that the delay, that is the number of times a symbol of the text is compared to symbols of the pattern, is less than $\lfloor \log _{\Phi }(k+1)\rfloor$ , where Φ is the golden ration $(1+{\sqrt {5}})/2$ .
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] In 1993, an algorithm was given that has a delay bounded by $\min(1+\lfloor \log _{2}k\rfloor ,|\Sigma |)$ where Σ is the size of the alphabet (of the pattern).
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] A real-time version of KMP can be implemented using a separate failure function table for each character in the alphabet.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] If a mismatch occurs on character x in the text, the failure function table for character x is consulted for the index i in the pattern at which the mismatch took place.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] This will return the length of the longest substring ending at i matching a prefix of the pattern, with the added condition that the character after the prefix is x .
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] With this restriction, character x in the text need not be checked again in the next phase, and so only a constant number of operations are executed between the processing of each index of the text.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] This satisfies the real-time computing restriction.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] Booth's algorithm uses a modified version of the KMP preprocessing function to find the lexicographically minimal string rotation.
[src:kmp-string-matching/knuth-morris-pratt-algorithm] The failure function is progressively calculated as the string is rotated.
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] In computer science, the **Rabin–Karp algorithm** or **Karp–Rabin algorithm** is a string-searching algorithm created by Richard M.
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] Rabin (1987) that uses hashing to find an exact match of a pattern string in a text.
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] It uses a rolling hash to quickly filter out positions of the text that cannot match the pattern, and then checks for a match at the remaining positions.
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] Generalizations of the same idea can be used to find more than one match of a single pattern, or to find matches for more than one pattern.
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] To find a single match of a single pattern, the expected time of the algorithm is linear in the combined length of the pattern and text, although its worst-case time complexity is the product of the two lengths.
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] To find multiple matches, the expected time is linear in the input lengths, plus the combined length of all the matches, which could be greater than linear.
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] In contrast, the Aho–Corasick algorithm can find all matches of multiple patterns in worst-case time and space linear in the input length and the number of matches (instead of the total length of the matches).
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] A practical application of the algorithm is detecting plagiarism.
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] Given source material, the algorithm can rapidly search through a paper for instances of sentences from the source material, ignoring details such as case and punctuation.
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] Because of the abundance of the sought strings, single-string searching algorithms are impractical.
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] A naive string matching algorithm compares the given pattern against all positions in the given text.
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] Each comparison takes time proportional to the length of the pattern, and the number of positions is proportional to the length of the text.
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] Therefore, the worst-case time for such a method is proportional to the product of the two lengths.
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] In many practical cases, this time can be significantly reduced by cutting short the comparison at each position as soon as a mismatch is found, but this idea cannot guarantee any speedup.
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] The Rabin–Karp algorithm instead achieves its speedup by using a hash function to quickly perform an approximate check for each position, and then only performing an exact comparison at the positions that pass this approximate check.
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] A hash function is a function which converts every string into a numeric value, called its *hash value*; for example, we might have `hash("hello")=5`.
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] If two strings are equal, their hash values are also equal.
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] For a well-designed hash function, the inverse is true, in an approximate sense: strings that are unequal are very unlikely to have equal hash values.
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] The Rabin–Karp algorithm proceeds by computing, at each position of the text, the hash value of a string starting at that position with the same length as the pattern.
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] If this hash value equals the hash value of the pattern, it performs a full comparison at that position.
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] In order for this to work well, the hash function should be selected randomly from a family of hash functions that are unlikely to produce many false positives, that is, positions of the text which have the same hash value as the pattern but do not actually match the pattern.
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] These positions contribute to the running time of the algorithm unnecessarily, without producing a match.
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] Additionally, the hash function used should be a rolling hash, a hash function whose value can be quickly updated from each position of the text to the next.
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] Recomputing the hash function from scratch at each position would be too slow.
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] Lines 2, 4, and 6 each require O(*m*) time.
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] However, line 2 is only executed once, and line 6 is only executed if the hash values match, which is unlikely to happen more than a few times.
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] Line 5 is executed O(*n*) times, but each comparison only requires constant time, so its impact is O(*n*).
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] Naively computing the hash value for the substring `s[i+1..i+m]` requires O(*m*) time because each character is examined.
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] Since the hash computation is done on each loop, the algorithm with a naive hash computation requires O(*mn*) time, the same complexity as a straightforward string matching algorithm.
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] For speed, the hash must be computed in constant time.
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] The trick is the variable `hs` already contains the previous hash value of `s[i..i+m-1]`.
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] If that value can be used to compute the next hash value in constant time, then computing successive hash values will be fast.
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] The trick can be exploited using a rolling hash.
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] A rolling hash is a hash function specially designed to enable this operation.
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] A trivial (but not very good) rolling hash function just adds the values of each character in the substring.
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] This simple function works, but will result in statement 5 being executed more often than other more sophisticated rolling hash functions such as those discussed in the next section.
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] Good performance requires a good hashing function for the encountered data.
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] If the hashing is poor (such as producing the same hash value for every input), then line 6 would be executed O(*n*) times (i.e. on every iteration of the loop).
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] Because character-by-character comparison of strings with length *m* takes O(*m*) time, the whole algorithm then takes a worst-case O(*mn*) time.
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] The key to the Rabin–Karp algorithm's performance is the efficient computation of hash values of the successive substrings of the text.
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] The Rabin fingerprint is a popular and effective rolling hash function.
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] The hash function described here is not a Rabin fingerprint, but it works equally well.
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] It treats every substring as a number in some base, the base being usually the size of the character set.
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] Technically, this algorithm is only similar to the true number in a non-decimal system representation, since for example we could have the "base" less than one of the "digits".
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] See hash function for a much more detailed discussion.
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] The essential benefit achieved by using a rolling hash such as the Rabin fingerprint is that it is possible to compute the hash value of the next substring from the previous one by doing only a constant number of operations, independent of the substrings' lengths.
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] We can then compute the hash of the next substring, "bra", from the hash of "abr" by subtracting the number added for the first 'a' of "abr", i.e.
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] 97 × 2562, multiplying by the base and adding for the last a of "bra", i.e.
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] If the substrings in question are long, this algorithm achieves great savings compared with many other hashing schemes.
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] Theoretically, there exist other algorithms that could provide convenient recomputation, e.g. multiplying together ASCII values of all characters so that shifting substring would only entail dividing the previous hash by the first character value, then multiplying by the new last character's value.
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] The limitation, however, is the limited size of the integer data type and the necessity of using modular arithmetic to scale down the hash results.
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] Meanwhile, naive hash functions do not produce large numbers quickly, but, just like adding ASCII values, are likely to cause many hash collisions and hence slow down the algorithm.
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] Hence the described hash function is typically the preferred one in the Rabin–Karp algorithm.
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] The Rabin–Karp algorithm is inferior for single pattern searching to Knuth–Morris–Pratt algorithm, Boyer–Moore string-search algorithm and other faster single pattern string searching algorithms because of its slow worst case behavior.
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] However, it is a useful algorithm for multiple pattern search.
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] We assume all the substrings have a fixed length *m*.
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] A naïve way to search for *k* patterns is to repeat a single-pattern search taking O(*n*+*m*) time, totaling in O((*n*+*m*)*k*) time.
[src:kmp-string-matching/rabin-karp-algorithm] In contrast, the above algorithm can find all *k* patterns in O(*n*+*km*) expected time, assuming that a hash table check works in O(1) expected time.
[src:kmp-string-matching/string-searching-algorithm] A **string-searching algorithm**, sometimes called **string-matching algorithm**, is an algorithm that searches a body of text for portions that match by pattern.
[src:kmp-string-matching/string-searching-algorithm] In practice, the method of feasible string-search algorithm may be affected by the string encoding.
[src:kmp-string-matching/string-searching-algorithm] In particular, if a variable-width encoding is in use, then it may be slower to find the *N*th character, perhaps requiring time proportional to *N*.
[src:kmp-string-matching/string-searching-algorithm] This may significantly slow some search algorithms.
[src:kmp-string-matching/string-searching-algorithm] One of many possible solutions is to search for the sequence of code units instead, but doing so may produce false matches unless the encoding is specifically designed to avoid it.
[src:kmp-string-matching/string-searching-algorithm] The most basic case of string searching involves one (often very long) string, sometimes called the *haystack*, and one (often very short) string, sometimes called the *needle*.
[src:kmp-string-matching/string-searching-algorithm] The goal is to find one or more occurrences of the needle within the haystack.
[src:kmp-string-matching/string-searching-algorithm] One might request the first occurrence of "to", which is the fourth word; or all occurrences, of which there are 3; or the last, which is the fifth word from the end.
[src:kmp-string-matching/string-searching-algorithm] Very commonly, however, various constraints are added.
[src:kmp-string-matching/string-searching-algorithm] For example, one might want to match the "needle" only where it consists of one (or more) complete words—perhaps defined as *not* having other letters immediately adjacent on either side.
[src:kmp-string-matching/string-searching-algorithm] In that case a search for "hew" or "low" should fail for the example sentence above, even though those literal strings do occur.
[src:kmp-string-matching/string-searching-algorithm] Another common example involves "normalization".
[src:kmp-string-matching/string-searching-algorithm] Finally, for strings that represent natural language, aspects of the language itself become involved.
[src:kmp-string-matching/string-searching-algorithm] For example, one might wish to find all occurrences of a "word" despite it having alternate spellings, prefixes or suffixes, etc.
[src:kmp-string-matching/string-searching-algorithm] Another more complex type of search is regular expression searching, where the user constructs a pattern of characters or other symbols, and any match to the pattern should fulfill the search.
[src:kmp-string-matching/string-searching-algorithm] where the "?" conventionally makes the preceding character ("u") optional.
[src:kmp-string-matching/string-searching-algorithm] This article mainly discusses algorithms for the simpler kinds of string searching.
[src:kmp-string-matching/string-searching-algorithm] A similar problem introduced in the field of bioinformatics and genomics is the maximal exact matching (MEM).
[src:kmp-string-matching/string-searching-algorithm] Given two strings, MEMs are common substrings that cannot be extended left or right without causing a mismatch.
[src:kmp-string-matching/string-searching-algorithm] A simple and inefficient way to see where one string occurs inside another is to check at each index, one by one.
[src:kmp-string-matching/string-searching-algorithm] First, we see if there is a copy of the needle starting at the first character of the haystack; if not, we look to see if there's a copy of the needle starting at the second character of the haystack, and so forth.
[src:kmp-string-matching/string-searching-algorithm] In this approach, backtracking is avoided by constructing a deterministic finite automaton (DFA) that recognizes a stored search string.
[src:kmp-string-matching/string-searching-algorithm] These are expensive to construct—they are usually created using the powerset construction—but are very quick to use.
[src:kmp-string-matching/string-searching-algorithm] For example, the DFA shown to the right recognizes the word "MOMMY".
[src:kmp-string-matching/string-searching-algorithm] This approach is frequently generalized in practice to search for arbitrary regular expressions.
[src:kmp-string-matching/string-searching-algorithm] Knuth–Morris–Pratt computes a DFA that recognizes inputs with the string to search for as a suffix, Boyer–Moore starts searching from the end of the needle, so it can usually jump ahead a whole needle-length at each step.
[src:kmp-string-matching/string-searching-algorithm] Baeza–Yates keeps track of whether the previous *j* characters were a prefix of the search string, and is therefore adaptable to fuzzy string searching.
[src:kmp-string-matching/string-searching-algorithm] The bitap algorithm is an application of Baeza–Yates' approach.
[src:kmp-string-matching/string-searching-algorithm] Faster search algorithms preprocess the text.
[src:kmp-string-matching/string-searching-algorithm] After building a substring index, for example a suffix tree or suffix array, the occurrences of a pattern can be found quickly.
[src:kmp-string-matching/string-searching-algorithm] As an example, a suffix tree can be built in $\Theta (n)$ time, and all z occurrences of a pattern can be found in $O(m)$ time under the assumption that the alphabet has a constant size and all inner nodes in the suffix tree know what leaves are underneath them.
[src:kmp-string-matching/string-searching-algorithm] The latter can be accomplished by running a DFS algorithm from the root of the suffix tree.
[src:kmp-string-matching/string-searching-algorithm] Some search methods, for instance trigram search, are intended to find a "closeness" score between the search string and the text rather than a "match/non-match".
[src:kmp-string-matching/string-searching-algorithm] These are sometimes called "fuzzy" searches.
[src:kmp-string-matching/string-searching-algorithm] The various algorithms can be classified by the number of patterns each uses.
[src:kmp-string-matching/string-searching-algorithm] In the following compilation, *m* is the length of the pattern, *n* the length of the searchable text, and *k* = |Σ| is the size of the alphabet.
[src:kmp-string-matching/string-searching-algorithm] The **Boyer–Moore string-search algorithm** has been the standard benchmark for the practical string-search literature.
[src:kmp-string-matching/string-searching-algorithm] In the following compilation, *M* is the length of the longest pattern, *m* their total length, *n* the length of the searchable text, *o* the number of occurrences.
[src:kmp-string-matching/string-searching-algorithm] Naturally, the patterns can not be enumerated finitely in this case.
[src:kmp-string-matching/string-searching-algorithm] They are represented usually by a regular grammar or regular expression.
[src:kmp-string-matching/string-searching-algorithm] Other classification approaches are possible.
[src:kmp-string-matching/string-searching-algorithm] One of the most common uses preprocessing as main criteria.
[src:kmp-string-matching/string-searching-algorithm] In real-time string matching, one requires the matcher to output a response after reading each character of the text, that indicates whether this is the last character of a match.
[src:kmp-string-matching/string-searching-algorithm] The response has to be given within constant time.
[src:kmp-string-matching/string-searching-algorithm] For the more lenient version, if one does not mind that the preprocessing time and memory requirement dependend on the size of the alphabet, a real-time solution is provided by automaton matching.
[src:kmp-string-matching/string-searching-algorithm] Zvi Galil developed a method to turn certain algorithms into real-time algorithms, and applied it to produce a variant of the KMP matcher that runs in real time under the strict requirement.
[src:kmp-string-matching/string-searching-algorithm] In this version of the string searching problem, there is a special symbol, ø (read: don't care), which can match any other symbol (including another ø).
[src:kmp-string-matching/string-searching-algorithm] Don't care symbols can appear either in the pattern or in the text.
[src:kmp-string-matching/string-searching-algorithm] In 2002, an algorithm for this problem that runs in $O(n\log m)$ time has been given by Richard Cole and Ramesh Hariharan, improving on a solution from 1973 by Fischer and Paterson that has complexity $O(n\log m\log k)$ , where *k* is the size of the alphabet.
[src:kmp-string-matching/string-searching-algorithm] Another algorithm, claimed simpler, has been proposed by Clifford and Clifford.
